From 7cd0c72b6aea67ce73aaa8e78843ee4e068d30a3 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Claude <claude@anthropic.com>
Date: Wed, 15 Jul 2026 20:20:16 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 1/4] Add Planner role and pipeline stage (item 4)

New workflow stage between Engineering's release and the Production
Manager's release-to-Fabrication step: a Planner now owns assigning
parts to a unit before handing it to the Production Manager.

Schema: added Planned to ProductionReleaseStatus (migration
20260715190000_add_planner_stage). Flow is now:
  Engineering releases -> AwaitingRelease (Planner's queue)
    -> Planner adds parts, releases -> Planned (Manager's queue)
    -> Manager releases -> Released -> Fabrication starts -> Started

Backend:
- New unit:plan permission, new "Planner" system role (unit:view,
  unit:plan, part:view, part:manage, department:view, process:view)
- GET /units/planner-queue - engineering-released units not yet planned
- POST /units/:id/mark-planned - requires at least one part exists,
  transitions AwaitingRelease -> Planned
- releaseToProduction() now requires Planned (was AwaitingRelease) -
  the Production Manager can no longer release a unit the Planner
  hasn't actually looked at
- managerSummary()'s "awaitingRelease" bucket (the Manager's actionable
  queue) now correctly means Planned, not AwaitingRelease; added a
  separate awaitingPlanning bucket for units still with the Planner

Frontend: new /planner-dashboard page. Left panel is a draggable
palette of Part Types; each queued unit is a drop target - dragging a
part type onto a unit calls the existing POST /units/:unitId/parts
(which already auto-generates routed tasks from that part type's
process route, no new logic needed there). "Release to Production
Manager" button per unit, disabled until it has at least one part.
